                <h2>When Do You Actually Need a Kanban for Account Opening</h2>
<p>Once you're managing account opening requests for 3+ media platforms simultaneously, manual tracking starts to break down. The client says they've submitted their documents, but you can't confirm if the platform received them. A top-up request has been pending for 3 days and nobody knows where it got stuck. During monthly reconciliation, you discover an account was never verified—but no one remembers where the process stalled.</p>
<p>The core value of a kanban is turning "information living in someone's head" into "information visible on the board." Every account opening request, from intake to completion, becomes visible, traceable, and assigned to a responsible person.</p>
<h2>SOP: Building and Using Your Agency Account Opening Kanban</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Define Your Board Columns and Statuses</h3>
<p>Columns represent the key stages in the account opening workflow. Set up these 7 columns in this specific order:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Not Started</strong>: Client contacted but no materials submitted</li>
<li><strong>Materials In Progress</strong>: Client preparing qualification documents</li>
<li><strong>Awaiting Submission</strong>: Documents complete, waiting to submit application</li>
<li><strong>Under Review</strong>: Platform reviewing qualifications</li>
<li><strong>Awaiting Top-Up Config</strong>: Account approved, waiting for funds</li>
<li><strong>Awaiting Account Verification</strong>: Top-up complete, waiting for first transaction verification</li>
<li><strong>Completed</strong>: All stages verified</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Note</strong>: If a column shows no card movement for 48 hours, platform review policies may have changed—contact your AM proactively.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Step 2: Create Required Card Fields</h3>
<p>Each card represents one account opening task and must include:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Field</th>
<th>Instructions</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Client Code</td>
<td>Use internal codes, never full client names</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Platform</td>
<td>Meta / Google / TikTok / Pinterest, etc.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Account Type</td>
<td>Direct / Agency Sub-account / Reseller</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Submission Date</td>
<td>Date ops first submitted to platform</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Owner</td>
<td>Operations team member responsible</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Estimated Live Date</td>
<td>Confirmed with AM</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Notes</td>
<td>Special qualification requirements or historical issues</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Step 3: Set Card Transition Rules</h3>
<p>When moving cards between columns, these rules apply:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Only the current-stage owner can move cards.</strong> For example, only the ops colleague managing that platform can move cards out of "Under Review."</li>
<li><strong>Every move requires a reason.</strong> When moving from "Under Review" to "Awaiting Top-Up Config," note: "Approved. Account ID: ACT_xxx."</li>
<li><strong>Auto-alerts for overdue cards.</strong> Set maximum time limits per column using your kanban tool's automation:</li>
<li>Materials In Progress: Max 5 business days</li>
<li>Under Review: Max 7 business days (varies by platform)</li>
<li>Awaiting Account Verification: Max 3 business days</li>
</ol>
<h3>Step 4: Configure Alert Notifications</h3>
<p>Set triggers at these stages to reduce manual follow-up:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>24 hours after entering "Under Review"</strong>: Remind ops to send confirmation email to platform AM</li>
<li><strong>48+ hours in "Awaiting Top-Up Config"</strong>: Remind finance to confirm payment receipt</li>
<li><strong>72+ hours in "Awaiting Account Verification"</strong>: Remind ops to run first transaction test</li>
<li><strong>Any card exceeding column threshold</strong>: Auto-mention owner and post in team group</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 5: Weekly Review Routine</h3>
<p>Spend 10 minutes on Monday morning reviewing the board:</p>
<ol>
<li>Scan "Not Started" column—if more than 3 cards, proactively reach out to clients</li>
<li>Scan "Under Review" for cards older than 10 days—mark as high priority</li>
<li>Scan "Completed" for new additions this week—track weekly completion rate</li>
<li>Export status change log for monthly reporting</li>
</ol>
<h2>Quick Troubleshooting</h2>
<p><strong>Q: Client keeps revising documents. How do I keep records clean?</strong></p>
<p>Use a version log in the card notes:<br />
- v1.0 (Oct 8): Business license copy<br />
- v1.1 (Oct 12): Added legal representative ID<br />
- v2.0 (Oct 15): Final version, approved</p>
<p>Never delete historical versions—keeping the audit trail aids future reviews.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Same client, multiple platforms. How do I avoid confusion?</strong></p>
<p>Use tagging. Add "Platform" and "Client Code" tags to every card. Add a filter bar at the top of your board to instantly view all cards for a specific client or platform.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Which kanban tool do you recommend?</strong></p>
<p>For teams under 5 people: Feishu (Lark) Multi-dimensional Tables or Notion—both free with automation rules. For teams of 10+: Jira or Monday, which offer better permission management and reporting.</p>
<h2>A Real Example</h2>
<p>A utility app's overseas operations team, before the kanban: Average opening cycle was 12 days, with frequent "submitted and forgotten" situations.</p>
<p>After implementing the kanban: With SOPs embedded in board rules, the average cycle dropped to 7 days. Overdue card alerts reduced "Under Review" follow-up misses by 80%. The team lead reported: "Now I just check the board weekly—no need to chase everyone for status updates."</p>
<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
<p>The account opening kanban isn't a complex management tool. Its essence is consolidating information scattered across chat logs and emails into one visual interface. The keys are <strong>clear column definitions, explicit transition rules, and reliable alerting</strong>. Start with a minimal setup and iterate after two weeks—don't chase a perfect template from day one.</p>
